MOESM2_ESM.csv file has these columns with train test splits in them:

"3 temporal (2011, 2012, 2013), 3 chemotype-based (aminohetaryl, aryl_c1_amide, c1_hetaryl_alkyl), 1 random = 7 total."

What does that mean?

1. Temporal splits (2011, 2012, 2013)                                                                                                                            
  Compounds are assigned to train/test based on when they were measured. E.g. temporal_2012_split: compounds measured before 2012 → train, compounds from 2012  
  onward → test. This simulates real drug discovery — you train on historical data and predict on future compounds. It's the most realistic evaluation of       
  prospective performance.   
    - Medicinal chemist, boss asks you to develop inhibitor for a protein, start with X amount of compounds, experimentally test them, binding affinities, want more potency, want to optimise for osome measurement, ML model to tell you what tto buy next, all can do, train on small molecs tested so far, so temporal split, dont care about what sub structures are in small molecs, just want to know what I should buy next
    - What small molecs do I make next, 
    - Say I care about potency, X examples, 2 or 3 that are really potent, train ML model on all data, useful to me to say, heres the ones om thinking of making, natural prediction is make the ones with high predictive potency, temporal split because, assigned all of molecules to training set that made already, and labels for
2. Chemotype-based (scaffolds) splits (aminohetaryl, aryl_c1_amide, c1_hetaryl_alkyl)                                                                                      
  Compounds are grouped by their chemical scaffold/series. One chemotype is held out as the test set, the others train. This tests whether your model can
  generalise across chemical series — a much harder task than interpolating within a series. Named after the three structural classes in the PDE10A dataset.
  - scaffold has greatger potency than another, tested 3 chemotypes, in this case trying to see if can generalise : 1. can you interpolate within that chemotype while retaining that core scaffold, useful to know how making small changes will affect something like my binding affinity, call this lead optimisation , can also use that same data for, can I genreaise between scaffolds now, 
3. Random split
  Compounds are randomly shuffled into train/test/val. This is the standard ML approach but the easiest — test compounds are structurally similar to training
  compounds, so performance is typically inflated vs. real-world use.

Why this matters: 7 splits let me directly compare how the same model performs under different generalisation pressures. A model that looks great on random splits may fail badly on temporal or chemotype splits.

